comments.text: just done something similar for my FYP. Me and my team has been putting efforts into making accurate prints on PP3DP Printers. We have used thin walls and small cylinders for the test. It turns out that the software basically only accept printing two layers of walls and 0.5mm is the starting point where it starts to print things out and it turns out to be about 1-1.1mm. So we also find the gap between two layered walls and three layered walls(or say two layers with fill). It jumps at about 1.48mm where it starts to print infills. I don't know about other machines but seems like this could help us to recognize how the slicing program works in the computer and hence how is the error when the model scales up.

comments.text: This is a very useful tool for those who create their own objects (you know what to stay away from), as well as those who would like to validate their slicer/nozzle settings against an existing object's parameters (you know what your printer/slicer is capable of and where it will fail spectacularly). I was mildly surprised to see that my 0.5mm nozzle and 0.4mm layer settings resolved the entire test, albeit with most of the smallest dimensions all printing exactly the same. This is also relatively quick to print and consumes relatively little material, so I think I will start printing these quite often as I alter slicer settings or experiment with a new filament vendor.

The death star on top of a platform with the caption, "Home Sweet Home!"  
It took a few days and a lot of back and forth between formats to create this. I likely went through 40 different files to complete it. I took the 3 parts of the death star and filled in their holed and merged them back together. Removing the hanger loop at the top wasn't easy and wasn't perfect. I was going to use a platform I found online but for whatever reason it contained a lot more surfaces than was apparent when I tried to add text, so I was forced to make that from scratch. Honestly I think if Sketchup had the tools and functions of AutoCAD from 15 years ago it would be far less frustrating. lol. I haven't attempted to print this item yet, but if anyone else would like to try it and let me know how it turns out I'd love to hear it.

I took a preexisting death star model and merged the 3 pieces of it back together after some editing both in Sketchup and Repetier Host. I created the platform for it entirely in Sketchup, and used Meshlab to convert between .stl, and dae when needed (and was needed often). At all major junctions I had to take an .stl to netfabb cloud to fill in holes and remove access lines. I resized the final item right in Repetier Host.

This thing is from a scan of an African cup turned and then carved from cocobolo. The original cup was scanned using a NextEngineSD. The resulting file had to be fused using the newer ScanPro 64bit SW.
BTW.. note the 3D Printer! This was printed using a beta version of Carl Raffles' CloneR1. a coreXY all metal masterpiece of a 3D Printer!
The details of how this object was scanned and printed along with the story of the CloneR1 will be discussed on the 3D Printing Today Podcast:
threedprintingtoday.libsyn.com
or search for "3D Printing Today" in iTunes or Stitcher radio

This stl file was printed using Simplify3D with three processes. One for the base which needed 6 shells and 20% infill to allow for the gentle slope of the base, the next process was for the middle part with 2 shells with 20% infill and a 2 shell top. The 3rd process was for the cup area with the carvings and it was 4 shells, 0% infill with a 1 shell bottom and no shells at the top.
The cup had an offset in the z axis of -1mm to ensure a nice flat bottom. Alternatively one can try and print this upside down and let the printer bridge the bottom inner part of the cup.

I noticed that nobody had a blowgun mouthpiece designed on here yet so I decided to make it my first contribution.  Blowgun mouthpieces I consider an important part to making any blowgun.  
I modeled this with FreeCad, because it's free, runs on Linux, Mac's, and Windows.  Theoretically I could also model this with freescad so that It's customizable, but I'll tackle that if there's demand.  
I've designed this to fit on the end of 1/2" Schedule 80 pvc pipe, that most home-made blowguns are made out of.  That's what I made mine out of.  I've included all the files needed to modify the design for other blowgun diameters.  I designed it to print without a raft and supports to decrease print time.  I try to design things without both whenever I can.  
I have tested this (version _1), and I did have to sand the end of the pvc pipe a bit to get it to fit.  So I redesigned all the files (latest version files have the "_2" on the end.  I increased the inner and outer diameter of the connector piece by 0.1mm.  Mostly because that's the resolution of my Replicator 2 Makerbot.  
Now I haven't tested this latest version ( _2) yet, but intend to within a month or so.  It's estimated to print in about 1 hour 30 minutes.  My original design took over 2 hours, so I did some work to get the print time down.  
UPDATE 1 :
Ok, so I had some trouble printing the _2 version.  Mostly the piece kept warping and coming off the build plate.  So I added 2 helper disks to keep it on the darn platform.  I also put another fillet in on the inside lip, just to make sure it would print right.  But after that they print fine now.  I've printed a couple of them.  I guess I should take pictures and post them, when I have time and remember that is.  
Update 2 : 
I actually printed this with ninja flex 2, which is flexible, and it really came out nice!  Although I think I should increase the wall depth of it just a smidge.  I thought it was a bit too flexy and wanted some more resistance to it.

title: Xabier Lete, Basque writer, poet, singer and politician

description.text:
Xabier Lete Bergaretxe (Oiartzun, Gipuzkoa, April 5, 1944 - San Sebastian, December 4, 2010) was a Basque writer, poet, singer and politician. He started to write from an early age and his publication of articles in the magazine "Zeruko Argiak" became quite usual. In 1965 he created a band of Basque Music with Mikel Laboa, Benito Lertxundi, Jotxean Artze, Jose Angel Irigarai and Lourdes Iriondo. The band was given the name of "Ez Dok Amairu", which disappeared in 1972, even though Xabier Lete kept on singing with Lourdes Iriondo, who, by that time, was his wife.
In 1968 Lete published his first book of poems and he won the Basque Literature Award in October 2009 for his last book of poems "Egunsentiaren esku izotzak" (Frozen hands of the dawn). He received a hard blow in 2005 when his wife Lourdes died for a disease. In April 2009 Lete was proclaimed member of the Academy of Wisdom, Science, Art and Literature, and in 2010, he was named member of honor of the Academy of the Basque Language. Xabier Lete died in that year, in the 4 December, due to an illness and after having been at two hospitals seriously ill. Gazterik hasi zen idazten, eta bere artikuluak ohiko bihurtu ziren Zeruko Argia aldizkarian. title: Rear suspension mounts for a Tamiya Lunchbox

description.text:
The Tamiya Lunchbox is an old design with a simple backend: the gearbox pivots on an 8mm ABS plastic rod and is attached on both sides to sprung suspension. This simple design is cheap (which is great when you have a 7 year old destroying your buggy!) but puts a lot of stress on the parts. In particular, the funky little bits of plastic that slide onto either side of the gearbox and screw in so the suspension can connect to them broke on our original.  
We 3D printed identical versions to the original in PLA but they broke so we thickened the design and 3D printed it in Taulman3D Nylon Bridge and that has stood the test of time (so far, at least).

My desk lamp sucked so I 3D printed a newer better lamp for my home office. This features integrated cooling channels and active cooling to keep five 10W LEDs under control. Thanks to the aggressive heating, the lamp remains cool to the touch.

Basically this is similar to other leveling jigs. I have modified the design to suit a Replicator 2X and use 3 magnets for extra stability.
also added extra file types so you can cater for different size magnets and indicators. Magnets
http://www.amazon.com/Magcraft-NSN0617-4-Inch-Magnets-20-Count/dp/B000SQK2JK Digital Indicator
http://www.ebay.com/itm/NEW-DIGITAL-DIAL-TEST-INDICATOR-GAUGE-0-5-0-0005-NIB-/300671127004?ssPageName=ADME:L:OC:AU:3160

These instructions are by Dan Ujvari which I found on Google Groups and are very helpful. "Re: [MakerBot] Re: leveling platform problems and filament guide tube takes off!
The trick is not to use the back screw at all until the front two are good. Also, completely ignore one of the heads. Your choice, left or right, but don't change mid-stream. Ignore one for the entire process. Just put the heads in the front left corner position, get a good drag on a biz card, then do the same on the front right position TO THE SAME HEAD. go back to the left to check if anything changed, if it did - go back to the right, etc... Once the front is good, then position the heads to the middle of the very back of the plate and adjust once TO THE SAME HEAD. You're done. It should take very little time... maybe two iterations on the front and one adjustment on the back. Now that you have the three points perfectly aligned, put the head you've been working with in the center of the plate. Not good? You've got a warped plate. If it is good, now check the other head... the one you've been ignoring all this time. Different? Your heads are misaligned. Everything good? Congrats. Now go buy aluminum arms from Bottleworks and save yourself from doing this over and over and over and over and over and over and over and over...." I do the same, but after I set the Extruder Nozzle height I then move the Extruder out of the way and then put this jig over the same first adjustment screw then the other two adjusting screws to dial in the exact height. (Note the white dots I put on the frame to help with lining up the jig with the adjustment screws.)
I also scale the object at 101.18%

title: Measure the speed of a motor

description.text:
In order to design the propeller for my 3D printed RC boat (coming soon!) I had to figure out the performance characteristics of some Johnson motors I bought on Ebay so I designed this little device.  
The first 3D printed part is the mount where you fit the Johnson or 540 type electric motor and a photodetector. The second 3D printed part is a rotor for the motor that breaks the beam twice per revolution. When connected to an Arduino this makes it easy to measure the relationships between current, acceleration and speed (RPM).

title: Chuwi Vi8 Tablet stand + xiaomi battery holder

description.text:
This is a bracket for the Chuwi Vi8 that holds a 10000mah Xiaomi Powerbank and doubles as a tablet stand, though only in portrait mode. The bracket should also fit the 20000 mah xiaomi powerbank as well, from what I know it is just longer so the bracket will fit. My Thingomatic has only a ~100mmx100mm build area, the length of the bracket is around 130mm, so to print it I rotated the bracket at 45 degrees and it fit within my build area. The Chuwi Vi8 weighs ~350 grams, the xiaomi 10000mah powerbank weighs ~250 grams. I estimate the normal run time for the chuwi vi8 is ~4-6 hours, I have not tested how long the battery life is with the 10000mah power bank but I am guessing 15 hours I hope. If you slap on a 20000 xiaomi powerbank, it will probably have enough juice for a whole week of constant usage. After you print it out, you should sand the inside that holds the battery, it is a very tight fit, just a minute of sanding is enough. You need to print out 2 of the same brackets, one bracket for each end of the powerbank. Update 6/25/15:
The thickness of the chuwi vi8 is ~ 10mm and the width is ~123mm, any tablet that is roughly the same size should work with the bracket. Batterylife is not as great as I hoped, the internal battery inside the chuwi is good for about 3 hours of youtube playback, with the battery pack it is good for an additional 6 hours of youtube playback, so the total batterylife when playing youtube videos is ~8-10 hours depending on the brightness and volume. A 20000mah powerbank should be good for a total of around 15 hours of continuous youtube playback.

If you have a 100x100mm build area, you need to rotate the bracket 45 degrees around the z axis, you will also need to shift the placement ~10mm in the x and y directions to get it to fit inside a 100x100 build area.  
You need to print out 2 brackets, one for each end of the powerbank.  
Some sanding will probably be required on the inside of the bracket where the powerbank fits into, the fit is very tight, a few minutes of sanding should be enough.

comments.author: hannuha

comments.text: The longer your print, the more heat begins to creep up your extruder body and filament. Not so much with ABS, but with PLA it becomes maleable at a much lower temperature. As extrusion and retraction occur more frequently during a print, the more opportunity your filament gets to bend and crimp to the point of nasty blobs and bulges that cause jams.
comments.author: hannuha

comments.text: I'm not so sure that the jamming problems are caused by heat. PLA goes through a glass transition (i.e. goes soft) at around 60C, and I doubt that the filament at the top of the extruder ever gets that hot. I had similar jamming issues and they went away completely by printing filament guides for the top and the bottom of the hobbed bolt (these ones: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:60719)http://www.thingiverse.com/thi.... There is a lot of room for the filament to move around within the extruder, and I think what happens is that the filament moves (perhaps after a fast retract or something) and bends a little off-axis with the extruder. Further extrusion after this then exacerbates the bending and can even snap the filament before it gets into the extruder (I have found folded up filament at the top of the extruder many times after a jam). Maybe you could put that fan to better use as a secondary cooling fan for the extruded PLA. Hope this helps!
